'''Williba''' is an [[unincorporated community]] in [[Lee County, Kentucky]], [[United States]], located on Fraley Creek, one-half mile from the confluence of the North Fork and the [[Kentucky River]].

Its post office opened on March 29, 1904, and was believed to have been originally named after [[Willoughby, Lincolnshire|Willoughby]], [[England]], from where the ancestors of the area's settlers were thought to have emigrated. The name "Williba" was supposedly a corruption adopted by its first postmaster to fit the name on a rubber stamp. The post office was later closed.

